1 Correlation

1.1 Pearsons Correlation

Welcome to the correlations tutorial. Your first task is to explore the bodyfat data from the R Package TH.data. The setup-script has created a smaller version of this dataset, now called bodyfat.tutorial. You should be able to find this data frame in your current global R environment. A description of the dataset can be found here: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/TH.data/TH.data.pdf or via ? bodyfat in the console. The study it was taken from can be found here: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1038/oby.2005.67 .

Now check the type of all variables in the data and create pairwise scatterplots of all metric and ordinal variables. Please do not hesitate to ask the tutors if there are any questions!

# check the name and class of all variables
kable(data.frame(lapply(bodyfat.tutorial, class)))
age DEXfat waistcirc hipcirc elbowbreadth kneebreadth
numeric numeric numeric numeric numeric numeric 
# create a scatterplot matrix of all variable combinations
pairs(bodyfat.tutorial)

Now pick a pair of variables that appear to be highly correlated and create a single scatterplot of those two. Then calculate the Pearsons and Spearmans Correlation Coefficients and interpret the results. Which type of correlation would be more appropriate?

# create a single scatterplot for close inspection and add the correlation coefficients
plot(bodyfat$waistcirc, bodyfat$DEXfat)
legend(x = "topleft", 
       legend = paste("Pearson's r:", 
                      round(cor(bodyfat$waistcirc, 
                                bodyfat$DEXfat, 
                                method = "pearson"), 
                            2),
                      "Spearman's r:",
                      round(cor(bodyfat$waistcirc, 
                                bodyfat$DEXfat, 
                                method = "spearman"), 
                            2)
                      )
       )

Now check the assumption for inferential statistics on Pearsons correlation, i.e.that the distributions of values for each of the two variables follow a Normal Distribution. This can be done by plotting a QQ-Plot comparing each variable to a Normal Distribution.

# plot a qqplot of the first variable
qqnorm(bodyfat$waistcirc, datax = T)
qqline(bodyfat$waistcirc, datax = T, col = 2)

# and of the second
qqnorm(bodyfat$DEXfat, datax = T)
qqline(bodyfat$DEXfat, datax = T, col = 2)

Now that you have checked if the distributional assumptions for inference on the correlation are met, you can go ahead and either use a more appropriate type of correlation or continue with Pearsons correlation and calculate confidence intervals for the estimated correlation.

# calculate confidence intervals for Pearson's correlation

# 90%
confidence_90 <- cor.test(bodyfat$waistcirc, bodyfat$DEXfat, method = "pearson", conf.level = 0.90)$conf.int

# 95%
confidence_95 <- cor.test(bodyfat$waistcirc, bodyfat$DEXfat, method = "pearson", conf.level = 0.95)$conf.int

# 99%
confidence_99 <- cor.test(bodyfat$waistcirc, bodyfat$DEXfat, method = "pearson", conf.level = 0.99)$conf.int

# display the three intervals in one table
kable(matrix(c(confidence_90, confidence_95, confidence_99), 
       byrow = T, 
       nrow = 3, 
       ncol = 2, 
       dimnames = list(Confidence = c("90%", "95%", "99%"), Bounds = c("Lower", "Upper"))
       ))
Lower Upper
90% 0.8526306 0.9308402
95% 0.8418517 0.9357654
99% 0.8186836 0.9444302

# create the single scatterplot for close inspection
plot(data.nl$var.1, data.nl$var.2)

       legend = paste("Pearson's r:", 
                      round(cor(data.nl$var.1, 
                                data.nl$var.2, 
                                method = "pearson"), 
                            2),
                      "Spearman's r:",
                      round(cor(data.nl$var.1, 
                                data.nl$var.2, 
                                method = "spearman"), 
                            2)
                      )
       )

To better understand how Spearmans Rank Correlation works, now transform var.1 and var.2 from data.nl by creating two columns (i.e.new variables), each containing the rank of an observation based on var.1 / var.2 . Hint: An R function you could use sounds a lot like what you want it to do

After creating these two new variables, plot them in a scatterplot and calculate Pearsons correlation coefficient. Then compare the result to you previously obtained two correlations. What do you notice?

# create a new column of ranks based on var.2
data.nl$var.1.rank <- rank(data.nl$var.1, ties.method = "average")
data.nl$var.2.rank <- rank(data.nl$var.2, ties.method = "average")


# create the  scatterplot and calculate the correlation
plot(data.nl$var.1.rank, data.nl$var.2.rank)
legend(x = "topleft", 
       legend = paste("Pearson's r:", 
                      round(cor(data.nl$var.1.rank, 
                                data.nl$var.2.rank, 
                                method = "pearson"), 
                            2)
                      )
       )

2 Regression

2.1 Exercise 1 - bodyfat data

We want to take a look at the bodyfat data set in package TH.data again. The setup-script has already loaded the dataset. A description of the dataset can be found by typing ?bodyfat in the console.

2.1.1 Model selection

The authors stated objective was to develop improved predictive regression equations for body fat content derived from common anthropometric measurements. We now want to reproduce their results. The response variable will therefore be DEXfat. All the variables in the dataset have potential explanatory power and are thus potential explanatory variables.

First take a look at the scatterplot of DEXfat and waistcirc again:

plot(bodyfat$waistcirc,bodyfat$DEXfat)
legend(x = "topleft", 
       legend = paste("Pearson's r:", 
                      round(cor(bodyfat$waistcirc, 
                                bodyfat$DEXfat, 
                                method = "pearson"), 
                            2),
                      "Spearman's r:",
                      round(cor(bodyfat$waistcirc, 
                                bodyfat$DEXfat, 
                                method = "spearman"), 
                            2)
                      )
       )

Now create a simple linear model with DEXfat as response and waistcirc as explanatory variable, take a look at the coefficients and draw the regression line into the scatterplot.

## create the model
body.lm1 <- lm(DEXfat ~ waistcirc, data=bodyfat)

## print the model
body.lm1
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = DEXfat ~ waistcirc, data = bodyfat)

## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)    waistcirc  
##    -31.0316       0.7074
## plot the scatter plot and add a line
plot(bodyfat$waistcirc,bodyfat$DEXfat)
abline(body.lm1$coefficients,col="blue",lwd=2)

What is the explained variance \(R^2\) by waistcirc?

We have seen the relation between \(R^2\) and Pearsons correlation \(\rho\) in simple linear regression. Now verify this in R.
Bonus: Verify the relation \(\widehat\beta_1\frac{\text{sd}(x)}{\text{sd}(y)}=\rho\) between Pearsons correlation and regression coefficient.

## R^2 of the simple linear regression model
summary(body.lm1)$r.squared
## [1] 0.8075781
## Pearson's correlation
cor.waist.fat <- cor(bodyfat$waistcirc,bodyfat$DEXfat, method="pearson")
## Pearson's correlation squared
cor.waist.fat^2
## [1] 0.8075781
## regression coefficient beta_1
beta1 <- body.lm1$coefficients['waistcirc']

## beta_1 scaled with the sample deviations equals Pearson's correlation
rho <- beta1*sd(bodyfat$waistcirc)/sd(bodyfat$DEXfat)
names(rho) <- "Pearson's r"
rho
## Pearson's r 
##   0.8986535

2.1.2 Model assessment

Evaluate the test error, i.e.the prediction error of the model applied to the test data.

## make predictions 
prediction <- predict.lm(body.lm.training,bodyfat.test)

## calculate the prediction error 
pred.error <- bodyfat.test$DEXfat - prediction

## and it's standard deviation
sd(pred.error)
## [1] 3.765598
## Residual/Total sum of squares 
RSS <- sum(pred.error^2)
TSS <- sum((bodyfat.test$DEXfat - mean(bodyfat.test$DEXfat))^2)


Rsquared <- 1-RSS/TSS
Rsquared
## [1] 0.7247262

Now fit the model to the complete data set and compare your result to the one given in the example of ?bodyfat

body.lm.final <- lm(DEXfat ~ hipcirc + kneebreadth + anthro3a, data=bodyfat)

Use the stats::plot.lm()-function (same as the plot-method on lm-objects) to assess the fit of the model. Check ?plot.lm for more detail on the function.

  1. Is there structure in the residuals left?
  2. Are the residuals approximately normally distributed?
  3. Is the assumption of constant variance satisfied?
  4. Are there individual data points with high leverage?
plot(body.lm.final)

## 1. Larger fitted values tend to have smaller residuals, hints at non-constant variance.
## 2. The QQ-plot looks fine.
## 3. In the third plot (sqrt(standardized residuals) vs Fitted values), a weak
##    trend in the form of "higher fitted values -> higher variance" is vaguely visible.
##    One could try if transformations of the explanatory variables 
##    like sqrt() or log() are an improvement. In this specific case, it might
##    justified to assume that the volume of bodyfat is not proportional to the
##    circumference, but rather the cubic root of the circumference.
## 4. The fourth plot (Residuals vs Leverage) shows no critical individual 
##    observations

2.2 Exercise 2 - Dosis data

2.2.1 Sample size: Case 1 - unadjusted

In some routinely collected data, you found a correlation between the dosis of a fequently given drug \(D\) and a biomarker \(B\), which is not known in the literature. Your aim is now to conduct a prospective study to examine whether this appeared merely at random in your Dosis data, or if there is indeed a relationship. How many subjects do you need to test this with a power of 90% to a significance level of 5% ?

## simulate the data set
set.seed(21)
N   <- 200
age <- runif (N,25,70) 
sex <- rbinom(N,1,0.5)
Dos <- 1+ rbeta(N,3,3) + 0.2*sex - 0.001 * age
Bio <- 50 + 25*Dos + age + 20*sex +  rnorm(N,0,25)  
  
Dosis <- data.frame(Dos,age,sex,Bio)


## calculate R^2  
R2_Dos     <-  summary(lm(Bio~Dos,data=Dosis))$r.squared

## calculate f^2
f2_Dos     <- R2_Dos/(1-R2_Dos) 



## calculate sample size of F-test for Dosis only
## the argument that is not given to the function pwr.f2.test() is calculated. 
## (Check also ?pwr.f2.test()). So in this case, the denominator degrees of 
## freedom v are calculated.
pwr.f2.test(1,f2=f2_Dos,power = 0.9)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 1
##               v = 118.6211
##              f2 = 0.08854495
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.9
## -> ceiling(v) + 2 = 121 subjects are needed

2.2.2 Statistical Inference: Case 1 - unadjusted

You now conducted your study and managed to include 150 subjects.

Now take a look at the Dosis.prospective150 data set. Can you reject your null hypothesis, that Dosis and Biomarker are independent?

## some artificial data

2.2.3 Sample Size: Case 2 - adjusted for age and sex

\(age\) and \(sex\) are known to influence the Biomarker (and have also an influence on the Dosis given), so the test should be adjusted for those two variables. How many subjects do you need in this case?

## calculate R^2  
R2_age.sex <-  summary(lm(Bio~age+sex,data=Dosis))$r.squared
R2_all     <-  summary(lm(Bio~.,data=Dosis))$r.squared

## calculate f^2
f2_adj     <- (R2_all - R2_age.sex)/(1 - R2_all)

## calculate sample size of F-test for Dosis, adjusted for age and sex
pwr.f2.test(u=1,f2=f2_adj,power = 0.9)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 1
##               v = 257.5637
##              f2 = 0.04078526
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.9
## -> ceiling(v) + 4 = 262 subjects are needed

Suppose the possible number of subjects is limited to 200 for logistical reasons. You now want to assess whether it is still worth conducting your study, i.e. you want to know the power for 200 subjects.

## First calculate the degrees of freedom v: subjects - degrees of the model
v = 200 - 4

## calculate power of F-test for 250 subjects
pwr.f2.test(u=1,v=v,f2_adj,sig.level = 0.05)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 1
##               v = 196
##              f2 = 0.04078526
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.8072557
## -> the power of the test would be 80.7%. In most contexts, this is still 
##  considered acceptable high. You might want to run your study even if you 
## could only include 200.

2.2.4 Statistical Inference: Case 2 - adjusted for age and sex

You managed to include 270 subjects into your prospective study.

Now take a look at the Dosis.prospective270 data set. Can you reject your null hypothesis, that Dosis and Biomarker are independent, adjusted for \(age\) and \(sex\)?

dosis.fullmodel <- lm(Bio ~ .        , data = Dosis.prospective270)
dosis.agesex    <- lm(Bio ~ age + sex, data = Dosis.prospective270)

## compare the variances with an F-test. 
## The easiest way to do that in R is the anova()-function on the two lm-objects:
anova(dosis.agesex,dosis.fullmodel)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: Bio ~ age + sex
## Model 2: Bio ~ Dos + age + sex
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq     F  Pr(>F)

3 A short step-by-step guide

3.1 First things first

Before any data analysis you will be about to conduct, one big question has to be clarified:
Will you perform confirmatory or exploratory analysis?

  • exploratory: your aim usually is to discover the variables that best explain the response
  • confirmatory: you have a specified hypothesis that seeks confirmation

In exploratory analysis, usually several regression models are specified and compared to select a winner of these candidate models.

For rigorous confirmatory analyses however, the analysis model needs to be specified before touching the data. The steps are

  1. model / hypothesis specification
  2. sample size calculation
  3. unbreak the blinding of the investigator
  4. model assessment
  5. statistical inference

3.2 Model selection

3.2.1 Model specification

  • Formulate what you want to investigate
    • What is the response variable?
    • Which potential explanatory variables should be considered?
  • Choose an adequate regression model, depending on the
    • response variable:
      • continuous \(\Rightarrow\) linear
      • binary \(\Rightarrow\) logistic (or probit)
      • categorical \(\Rightarrow\) ordinal
      • count \(\Rightarrow\) poisson
      • survival \(\Rightarrow\) coxPH,
    • structure of the data:
      • if the data are clustered (e.g.repeated measures) \(\Rightarrow\) mixed models, which include random effect terms, can be applied
      • other fitting approaches than minimizing the RSS can be useful (i.e.Lasso in high-dimensional data)

3.2.2 Model comparison

Model comparison is mainly relevant in exploratory settings. Popular methods are

  • ANOVA (for nested models only)
  • Comparisons of information criteria, e.g.AIC
  • Comparisons of likelihoods
  • (Test error comparisons via cross-validation)

These methods (especially ANOVA and AIC) are often used iteratively to select a favoured set of variables.

  • Forward selection: start with a minimal model and add the best variable in each step. Stop if the method finds no further improvement.
  • Backward selection: start with the maximal model and then drop the least informative variable in each step. Stop if the method finds no further improvement.

3.3 Sample size calculation

In exploratory analysis, sample size calculation is usually not feasible - in a confirmatory (prospective) setting,
the needed sample size can (and should) be calculated. But in order to do this, a few things need to be specified:

  • fully specified hypothesis, that means
    • a specified model, and
    • a statistical test
    • a significance level \(\alpha\)
  • the power one aspires to achieve (often set to 80% or 90%)
  • an assumed effect size

3.4 Model Assessment

After conducting any regression analysis, one should check the appropriateness of the model. There is no recommendend straightforward way to test for violations of the assumptions, but the important assumptions can be checked visually:

  1. that no structure in the residuals is apparent
  2. that the residuals are approximately normally distributed
  3. that the variance of the residuals is constant (homoscedastic)
  4. that there are no highly influential individuals (outliers)

In exploratory analysis, if any of the above seems violated, restart at model selection. In confirmative analysis, all one can still do is discussing the effect of these violations.

Another important method is assessing the prediction error (test error) for data not used to fit the model. Therefore, one splits the in two subsets, one set to fit (in this setting often called train) the model, the other to validate (test) it. An even more sophisticated way to do this is cross-validation.

3.5 Statistical Inference

In a confirmatory setting, one now can finally evaluate the initial hyphothesis.

4.1 on Power Analysis

  • A useful tool for power calculations for almost all kinds of tests is G*Power: http://gpower.hhu.de/. It tends to be technical, but has a good manual.

  • Cohen J.(1977), Statistical Power Analysis for the Behavioral Sciences - still one of the best works to understand effect sizes
